Now I have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Let me design the complete TDD implementation plan.

---

## TDD Implementation Plan: WebSocket Broadcasting for API Route Handlers

### Overview of the Approach

The plan follows strict TDD order: write failing tests first, then write the minimum implementation to make them pass. There are two separate work streams that must be sequenced carefully:

1. `server/test/cards.test.mjs` — the new test file
2. `server/api/cards.js` — the new router file
3. Modifications to `server/api/comments.js` — add broadcast to existing endpoint
4. Modifications to `server/index.js` — register the cards router
5. Modification to `server/package.json` — update the test script

---

### Step 0: Understand the Key Testing Challenge

The central challenge is how to test that HTTP endpoints call `broadcast()`. The solution from `ws.test.mjs` provides the pattern: start a real HTTP server with `initWs(server)` attached, connect a real WebSocket client using the `ws` package, and race the message listener against a timeout. However, this means tests cannot use the `createApp()` + bare `app.listen(0)` pattern from `comments.test.mjs` — they need the full `http.Server` + `initWs` initialization.

The key insight is that `broadcast` from `broadcaster.js` uses module-level singleton state (`clients` Set). Since Node.js caches ES modules, every import of `broadcaster.js` in the same process shares the same `clients` Set. This means a test that calls `initWs(server)` will cause any subsequent `broadcast()` call (including those triggered by fetch requests) to reach WebSocket clients connected to that server.

There is one important isolation concern: the `clients` Set is module-level. If `initWs` is called multiple times in the same process without `closeWs`, the previous set is replaced (the defensive reset in `initWs` at line 13-16 of `broadcaster.js` handles this). Each `describe` block must call `closeWs()` in its `after()` hook to reset state cleanly.

---

### Step 1: Write `server/test/cards.test.mjs` (RED phase)

This file is written first. All tests will fail because `server/api/cards.js` does not exist yet and `index.js` has not been updated.

**File header and imports:**

```javascript
import { describe, it, before, after } from 'node:test';
import assert from 'node:assert/strict';
import { createServer } from 'node:http';
import WebSocket from 'ws';
import { createApp } from '../index.js';
import { initDb, closeDb, createCard } from '../db/queries.js';
import { initWs, closeWs } from '../ws/broadcaster.js';
```

**Required helper functions** (modeled exactly after `ws.test.mjs`):

```javascript
// Start a full HTTP+WS server using Express app and initWs
async function startTestServerWithWs(app) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    const server = app.listen(0, () => {
      const { port } = server.address();
      initWs(server);
      resolve({
        server,
        baseUrl: `http://localhost:${port}`,
        wsUrl: `ws://localhost:${port}`,
      });
    });
  });
}

async function stopTestServer(server) {
  await closeWs();
  return new Promise((resolve) => server.close(resolve));
}

function connectWsClient(wsUrl) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const ws = new WebSocket(wsUrl);
    ws.once('open', () => resolve(ws));
    ws.once('error', reject);
  });
}

function waitForMessage(ws) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    ws.once('message', (data) => resolve(JSON.parse(data.toString())));
  });
}

function closeWsClient(ws) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    if (ws.readyState === WebSocket.CLOSED) return resolve();
    ws.once('close', resolve);
    ws.close();
  });
}

function withTimeout(promise, ms) {
  return Promise.race([
    promise,
    new Promise((_, reject) =>
      setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`Timed out after ${ms}ms`)), ms)
    ),
  ]);
}
```

**Why `startTestServerWithWs` calls `initWs` inside the `listen` callback:** The server's port is only available once listening has started, and `initWs` needs the `httpServer` reference to attach the `WebSocketServer`. This is the same pattern used in `server/index.js` at line 66-67.

**Why NOT use `createServer()` separately:** We need Express middleware (routing, JSON body parsing, CORS) to test HTTP endpoints. `createApp()` returns the Express app, and `app.listen()` returns the `http.Server`. We need that exact server instance to pass to `initWs`.

---

### Step 1a: Test Suite 1 — `POST /api/cards` (card creation with broadcast)

```javascript
describe('POST /api/cards', () => {
  let server, baseUrl, wsUrl;

  before(async () => {
    initDb(':memory:');
    const app = createApp();
    ({ server, baseUrl, wsUrl } = await startTestServerWithWs(app));
  });

  after(async () => {
    await stopTestServer(server);
    closeDb();
  });

  // ── HTTP behavior ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  it('returns 201 with created card on valid request', async () => {
    const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'My Card' }),
    });
    assert.strictEqual(res.status, 201);
  });

  it('response body has id, title, assignee, column, position, description, created_at', async () => {
    const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'Full Card', assignee: 'Alice', description: 'Desc' }),
    });
    const body = await res.json();
    assert.ok(body.id);
    assert.strictEqual(body.title, 'Full Card');
    assert.strictEqual(body.assignee, 'Alice');
    assert.ok(body.column);
    assert.ok(typeof body.position === 'number');
    assert.strictEqual(body.description, 'Desc');
    assert.ok(body.created_at);
  });

  it('returns 400 when title is missing', async () => {
    const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ assignee: 'Alice' }),
    });
    assert.strictEqual(res.status, 400);
  });

  it('400 response body has "error" field', async () => {
    const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({}),
    });
    const body = await res.json();
    assert.strictEqual(typeof body.error, 'string');
  });

  // ── WebSocket broadcast ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  it('broadcasts card:created event after successful creation', async () => {
    const ws = await connectWsClient(wsUrl);
    const msgPromise = waitForMessage(ws);
    await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'Broadcast Card' }),
    });
    const msg = await withTimeout(msgPromise, 500);
    assert.strictEqual(msg.event, 'card:created');
    await closeWsClient(ws);
  });

  it('card:created payload matches created card', async () => {
    const ws = await connectWsClient(wsUrl);
    const msgPromise = waitForMessage(ws);
    const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'Payload Check' }),
    });
    const card = await res.json();
    const msg = await withTimeout(msgPromise, 500);
    assert.strictEqual(msg.payload.id, card.id);
    assert.strictEqual(msg.payload.title, card.title);
    await closeWsClient(ws);
  });

  it('does not broadcast on 400 (missing title)', async () => {
    const ws = await connectWsClient(wsUrl);
    const unexpected = [];
    ws.on('message', (data) => unexpected.push(JSON.parse(data.toString())));
    await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({}),
    });
    await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 100));
    assert.strictEqual(unexpected.length, 0);
    await closeWsClient(ws);
  });

  // ── Broadcast resilience ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

  it('API succeeds (201) even when no WebSocket server is initialized', async () => {
    // This test uses a plain server without initWs — requires a separate server instance
    await closeWs(); // close the shared WS server first
    const isolatedApp = createApp();
    const { server: s2, baseUrl: b2 } = await new Promise((resolve) => {
      const srv = isolatedApp.listen(0, () =>
        resolve({ server: srv, baseUrl: `http://localhost:${srv.address().port}` })
      );
    });
    initDb(':memory:'); // already inited, but just to be safe — queries.js uses module singleton
    const res = await fetch(`${b2}/api/cards`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'No WS Card' }),
    });
    assert.strictEqual(res.status, 201);
    await new Promise((resolve) => s2.close(resolve));
    // Restart WS for the shared server — note: shared server is already listening,
    // but we closed WS. Re-init is needed for other tests.
  });
});
```

**Note on the resilience test:** The resilience test is slightly tricky because `broadcast()` is safe when `clients` is empty (it simply iterates an empty Set — no error). However, the test scenario is "broadcast does not crash the HTTP response". The simplest approach is: `broadcast()` is called in a `try-catch` in the route handler. When `clients` is empty, nothing happens. Testing this properly means verifying the API returns 201 even when broadcast would throw. A cleaner approach is to test this in isolation: call `closeWs()` to clear the WS singleton, then make the HTTP request. The `broadcast()` function will iterate an empty `clients` Set without error, so the 201 response proves it succeeded.

A cleaner alternative for the resilience test that avoids server lifecycle complexity:

```javascript
it('API returns 201 even when broadcast throws internally', async () => {
  // broadcast() is wrapped in try-catch in the route handler.
  // We verify this by checking the HTTP response is still 201 
  // when called normally — the broadcast error path is tested via
  // the "no clients connected" scenario (broadcast iterates empty Set safely).
  const ws = await connectWsClient(wsUrl);
  await closeWsClient(ws); // disconnect immediately
  await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 20)); // allow close to propagate
  const res = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/cards`, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ title: 'Resilience Card' }),
  });
  assert.strictEqual(res.status, 201);
});
```

---

### Step 1b: Test Suite 2 — `PATCH /api/cards/:id` (card update with broadcast)

```javascript
describe('PATCH /api/cards/:id', () => {
  let server, baseUrl, wsUrl, cardId;

